SIMPLE: emersion
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Emersion
<hw>E*mer"sion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧mersion</ets>. See <er>Emerge</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act of emerging, or of rising out of anything; <as>as,
<ex>emersion</ex> from the sea; <ex>emersion</ex> from obscurity or
difficulties.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their immersion into water and their <qex>emersion</qex> out of
the same.</q> <rj><qau>Knatchbull.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>The reappearance of a heavenly
body after an eclipse or occultation; <as>as, the <ex>emersion</ex> of
the moon from the shadow of the earth; the <ex>emersion</ex> of a star
from behind the moon.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Emery</ent>⟦br⟧
